The behaviour is funny with docker pull, it said in a UI on dockerhub that one can use "docker pull" now it's been replaced with "docker model pull". I tried "docker pull" again and it downloaded all the bytes but failed on some final validation step (my version of docker may not be recent enough also, worth trying again in the next docker release).

I do think it's important to make it really obvious that we are compatible pulling these "application/vnd.docker.ai.model.config.v0.1+json" files, so it's obvious we are on feature par with docker at least in terms of pulling this type of ai models.

Also minor nit, the european in me sometimes types "artefact" and it fails, might be worth considering making that an alias of "artifact".

Also worth exploring how we can take this .gguf file and run it in an inferencing tool like RamaLama.

@Luap99 while it would be nice to have a name, we should have a default based on the OCI Name perhaps?  The base name?

In RamaLama we either mount the single file artifact on /mnt/model/model.file and then the AI Model Runtime always looks for the file there.  With OCI Image models, we require that a symlink exists so we can mount the directory.  At least for the models we build. 

One issue going forward is there are multiple different OCI Model formats evolving.  We have our Model Car and Model Raw. Which we want the symlink.  Docker format and Ollama Format, soon we will add podman artifacts.  I am fine if Podman AI Model artifacts follow Docker format.  But a standard would be great.
